<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900820-0037</DOCNO><DOCID>900820-0037.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Nordstrom Inc.:   Company to Settle Charges   Of Violating Labor Laws</HL><DATE>08/20/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><CO>   NOBE LABOR</CO><IN>SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)</IN><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><LP>   Nordstrom Inc. said it agreed to settle charges ofviolating several federal labor laws in its handling of adispute with the United Food andamp; Commercial Workers Union.   In the tentative agreement with the National LaborRelations Board, Nordstrom doesn't admit guilt, nor is itrequired to pay a fine. But the retailer promised it wouldn'tallow certain alleged practices that resulted in charges thelabor board found to have potential merit. Those includediscrimination against employees taking part in unionactivities and promising workers additional benefits if theunions are decertified.</LP><TEXT>   The violations stemmed from a yearlong dispute with theUnited Food andamp; Commercial Workers locals 1001 and 367.Contract talks with the two locals, whose pacts coveringSeattle-area salespeople expired last year, broke down afterthe company proposed making union membership optional.   A spokesman for the unions declined to comment on theproposed settlement.</TEXT></DOC>